content:
The bug allowed the hacker to mint 219,200 LINK tokens (worth about $2.6 million); 4,503 ETH (~$1.6 million); 1,756,351 USDT (~$1.7 million); 1,412,048 USDC (~$1.4 million) and 667,989 DAI (~$680,000). That is $8.1 million in total. bZx said no user funds are at risk as the loss is being covered by its insurance fund.&nbsp;<br data-v-f87c67ca="">
<br data-v-f87c67ca="">
Marc Thalen, a lead engineer at Bitcoin.com, claims to have <a href="https://twitter.com/MarcThalen/status/1305354469354303488" data-v-f87c67ca="">initially identified the bug</a>. He said more than $20 million of bZx funds were at risk. Thalen himself tried the exploit out and created a loan using USDC (100 USD). "From this I retrieved iUSDC. I then sent this to myself practically duplicating the funds. I then created a claim for 200 USD," said Thalen.&nbsp;
